</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
Case IV: Misalignment
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
</lyxtabular>

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Case IV: The government wants to give the slots to those who value it the
 least
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Law enforcement: Slot is avoiding jail 
\begin_inset Formula $H>0>L$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{H}=y_{L}=y$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h=l>0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Driving licenses.
 Bad drivers more likely to get in trouble, so 
\begin_inset Formula $H>0>L$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{H}=y_{L}=y$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $h<l$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Procurement: Imagine there are high and low quality firms.
 The slot is the contract.
 Want to buy from high quality firms 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(H>L\right)$
\end_inset

 even though costs higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(l>h\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Without credit constriants, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{H}=h$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{L}=l$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Banerjee et al.
 2012: Alignment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{H}<1$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $L>0$
\end_inset

 so optimal to give leftover slots to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We will analyze 4 possible mechanisms:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The socially optimal mechanism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
All slots to the highest bidder: The 
\emph on
auction
\emph default
 mechanism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Pay to avoid missing out on a slot: The 
\emph on
monopoly
\emph default
 mechanism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Using testing to deter mimicry: The 
\emph on
testing
\emph default
 mechanism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We will characterize each mechanism and show when the bureaucrat will pick
 each one
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Banerjee et al.
 2012: Alignment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Candidate solution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p_{H} & =y_{L}+\epsilon,\:p_{L}=y_{L}\\
\pi_{H} & =1,\:\pi_{L}=\frac{1-N_{H}}{N_{L}}\\
t_{H} & =t_{L}=0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Low types can't mimic (can't afford 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{H}$
\end_inset

).
 High types won't mimic as long as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underbrace{h-\left(y_{L}+\varepsilon\right)}_{\text{slot for sure at }p_{H}}\geq\underbrace{\frac{1-N_{H}}{N_{L}}\left(h-y_{L}\right)}_{\text{slot w/pr }\left(1-N_{H}\right)/N_{L}\text{ at price }p_{L}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Banerjee et al.
 2012: Alignment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This can always be guaranteed for small enough 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Affordable to 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{H}>y_{L}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Feasible since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{L}$
\end_inset

 chosen to satisfy slot constraint
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

s such that this mechanism is in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Will the bureaucrat choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\in E$
\end_inset

? Given the fixed cost of breaking the rules, if he breaks them, he'll maximize
 his profits.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Banerjee et al.
 2012: Alignment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
How can the bureaucrat extract more rents? Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{L}$
\end_inset

 the highest price he can charge 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

s is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{H}=p_{H}^{*}=\min\left\{ y_{H},y_{L}+\left(h-y_{L}\right)\frac{N-1}{N_{L}}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 Auction mechanism
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p_{H} & =p_{H}^{*},\:p_{L}=y_{L}\\
\pi_{H} & =1,\:\pi_{L}=\frac{1-N_{H}}{N_{L}}\\
t_{H} & =t_{L}=0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Banerjee et al.
 2012: Alignment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The auction mechanism still leave 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

s positive surplus: 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{H}^{*}<y_{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Can the bureaucrat extract more?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
He needs to satisfy the mimicry constraint.
 So he can play with 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{L}$
\end_inset

 to do this and maybe get more money.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 the Monopoly mechanism.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p_{H} & =\tilde{p}_{H}\leq y_{H},\:p_{L}=y_{L}\\
\pi_{H} & =1,\:\pi_{L}=\min\left\{ \frac{h-\tilde{p}_{H}}{h-y_{L}},\frac{1-N_{H}}{1-N_{L}}\right\} \\
t_{H} & =t_{L}=0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Note, this mechanism is inefficient whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{L}<\left(1-N_{H}\right)/\left(1-N_{L}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Slots are wasted
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Banerjee et al.
 2012: Alignment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Will the bureaucrat prefer the auction or monopoly mechanism?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The profits to the bureaucrat from the monopoly mechanism are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{H}\left(\tilde{p}_{H}-p\right)+N_{L}\frac{h-\tilde{p}_{H}}{h-y_{L}}\left(y_{L}-p\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Note that at 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{p}=y_{L}+\left(h-y_{L}\right)\left(N-1\right)/N_{L}$
\end_inset

 he gets the auction mechanism profit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Profits are increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{p}_{H}$
\end_inset

 iff
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{H}>N_{L}\frac{y_{L}-p}{h-y_{L}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If this condition holds, the monopoly mechanism with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{p}_{H}=y_{H}$
\end_inset

 dominates.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Banerjee et al.
 2012: Alignment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Finally, consider the testing mechanism:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p_{H} & =\min\left\{ y_{H},h-\left(h-l\right)\frac{1-N_{H}}{N_{L}}\right\} ,\:p_{LS}=p_{LF}=y_{L}\\
\pi_{H} & =1,\:\pi_{LS}=\pi_{LF}=\frac{1-N_{H}}{N_{L}}\\
t_{H} & =0,\:t_{L}=\max\left\{ 0,\frac{1}{\delta}\min\left\{ \left(h-y_{L}\right)\frac{1-N_{H}}{N_{L}}-\left(h-y_{H}\right),\right.\right.\\
 & \qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\left.\left.\left(l-y_{L}\right)\frac{1-N_{H}}{N_{L}}\right\} \right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Aim: Use testing to relax the IC constraint that 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

s don't mimic 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

s
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Banerjee et al.
 2012: Alignment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Note testing here is completely wasteful: Nothing depends on the outcome.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 types more likely to pass, so don't want to reward passing (trying to discourag
e pretending to be 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 types can fail on purpose, so don't want to reward failing
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Testing relaxes the IC constraint though:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h-p_{H}\geq\left(h-y_{L}\right)\frac{1-N_{H}}{N_{L}}-\delta t_{L}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
RHS decreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{L}$
\end_inset

 so can increase 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{H}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Can't go past 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{H}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta t_{L}\leq h-y_{H}-\left(h-y_{L}\right)\frac{1-N_{H}}{N_{L}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Also can't scare away all the 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

s
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta t_{L}\leq\left(l-y_{L}\right)\frac{1-N_{H}}{N_{L}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Banerjee et al.
 2012: Alignment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This doesn't exhaust all possible mechanisms, but they're useful archetypes.
 So which one will the bureaucrat choose?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Scenario 1: Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(h-y_{L}\right)\frac{N-1}{N_{L}}+y_{L}\geq y_{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Now the auction mechanism extracts the most rents.
 The government gives the bureaucrat full discretion and sets 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to divide the surplus between them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Scenario 2: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(h-y_{L}\right)\frac{N-1}{N_{L}}+y_{L}<y_{H}$
\end_inset

 but testing is a) easy: 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=0$
\end_inset

, and b) effective, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{H}\leq h-\left(h-l\right)\frac{1-N_{H}}{N_{L}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Government can set a rule that price must be below 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(h-y_{L}\right)\frac{N-1}{N_{L}}+y_{L}$
\end_inset

 and there cannot be any testing.
 Bureaucrats with high 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 will follow this rule and choose the auction mechanism.
 Those with low 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 will break it and choose either the testing or monopoly mechanism.
 In equilibrium there are both bribes and inefficiency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Note that therefore the optimal rules depend on the degree of corruptibility
 of the bureaucrats.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Banerjee et al.
 2012: Alignment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Scenario 3: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(h-y_{L}\right)\frac{N-1}{N_{L}}+y_{L}<y_{H}$
\end_inset

 but testing is hard: 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\gg0$
\end_inset

 so bureaucrats don't use red tape.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Without rules the bureaucrats choose either auction or monopoly mechanism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
They choose the monopoly mechanism (which the govt dislikes) if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{H}>N_{L}\frac{y_{L}-p}{h-y_{L}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Government can set low 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to avoid monopoly mechanism
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Government may prefer to cap the price again.
 There will be bribery, and also inefficiency amongst those choosing the
 monopoly mechanism.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Banerjee et al.
 2012: Inability to Pay
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Focus on Banerjee (1997) special case: 
\begin_inset Formula $L>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{H}<1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h>l$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{H}=y_{L}=y<l$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{L}\left(t\right)=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Three mechanisms:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Auction mechanism:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p_{H} & =y,\;p_{L}=l-\frac{N_{L}}{1-N_{H}}\left(l-y\right)\\
\pi_{H} & =1,\:\pi_{L}=\frac{1-N_{H}}{N_{L}}\\
t_{H} & =t_{L}=0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 types prefer paying the higher price and getting the slot for sure.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Banerjee et al.
 2012: Inability to Pay
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument item:1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
2.
\end_layout

\end_inset

Testing mechanism:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p_{H} & =y,\:p_{L}=y\\
\pi_{H} & =1,\:\pi_{L}=\frac{1-N_{H}}{N_{L}}\\
t_{H} & =\frac{N_{H}+N_{L}-1}{N_{L}}\left(l-y\right),\:t_{L}=0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Satisfy the IC constraint by making 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 types do the test, even though they're guaranteed to pass.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument item:1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
3.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Lottery mechanism: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p_{H} & =y,\:p_{L}=y\\
\pi_{H} & =\pi_{L}=\frac{1}{N_{H}+H_{L}}\\
t_{H} & =0,\:t_{L}=0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Banerjee et al.
 2012: Inability to Pay
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Scenario: 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
With no rules, the bureaucrat prefers the lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 inefficient allocation of slots
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Suppose rule is set to require 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{H}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{L}=\left(1-N_{H}\right)/N_{L}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Now bureaucrat uses the testing mechanism.
 Yields same payoff as lottery.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To stop this the government can set rule that the auction mechanism must
 be followed.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Bureaucrats with high 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 will follow the rule.
 Bureaucrats with low 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 will use the testing mechanism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Bribery and red tape.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Alternatively the government could have the rule be the lottery.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
No corruption and no red tape.
 But misallocation
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Banerjee et al.
 2012: Misalignment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Focus on the following case:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $N_{H}>1$
\end_inset

: Slots are scarce.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $y_{L}=l>h=y_{H}$
\end_inset

: social and private values are misaligned
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $L<0$
\end_inset

: Low types should not have a slot.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Consider three types of mechanisms the bureaucrat might use
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Banerjee et al.
 2012: Misalignment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

testing + auction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p_{HS} & =p_{H}^{*},\:p_{HF}=p_{L}=l\\
\pi_{HS} & =1/N_{H},\:\pi_{HF}=\pi_{L}=0\\
t_{H} & =t_{H}^{*},\:t_{L}=0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{H}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{H}^{*}$
\end_inset

 solve
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
h-\delta t_{H}^{*}-p_{H}^{*} & =0\\
\left(1-\phi_{L}\left(t_{H}\right)\right)\left(l-p_{H}^{*}\right)-\delta t_{H}^{*} & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Note the IC constraint for the 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 types: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(1-\phi_{L}\left(t_{H}\right)\right)\left(l-p_{H}^{*}\right)-\delta t_{H}^{*}\leq0
\]

\end_inset

they have to prefer not getting the slot to pretending to be 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and getting it with some probability
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Banerjee et al.
 2012: Misalignment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument item:1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
2.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

auction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p_{H} & =p_{L}=l\\
\pi_{H} & =0,\:\pi_{L}=1/N_{L}\\
t_{H} & =0,\:t_{L}=0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Noone is tested, but the allocation is terrible: Only 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

s get slots
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument item:1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
3.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lottery
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p_{H} & =p_{L}=h\\
\pi_{H} & =\pi_{L}=1/\left(N_{L}+N_{H}\right)\\
t_{H} & =0,\:t_{L}=0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

