\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
People often do things that are costly to themselves and primarily benefit
 others.
 Why?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Rewards and punishments for prosocial behavior sometimes backfire.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Social pressure and norms successfully use honor and shame to direct behavior
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
People care about their 
\emph on
self-image
\emph default
.
 People want to think they are prosocial.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Develop a theory of prosocial behavior.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Heterogeneity in degree of altruism/greed
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
desire for social reputation/self-respect
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
People's behavior has 3 motivations 
\emph on
intrinsic, extrinsic, 
\emph default
and 
\emph on
reputational.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


