status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph on
(c)
\end_layout

\end_inset

The optimal effort level solves: 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{jj}^{*}=b_{jj}^{*}+\bar{\theta}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{00}^{*}=b_{00}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Besley & Ghatak 2005: Competing for Workers: Full Employment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Competition for workers and incentives interact in important ways
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
matching effect
\emph default
.
 Less heterogeneity in contracts compared to a world in which principals
 and agents don't match assortatively.
 When the participation constraint doesn't bind, incentive pay is lower.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
outside option effect.

\emph default
 Full employment drives profit-oriented principals' payoff to zero.
 Motivated agent's reservation utility is what she'd get by switching to
 the profit-oriented sector.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
When productivity is high in the profit-oriented sector, the mission-oriented
 sector has to pay more and use incentive pay more.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Even with a binding participation constraint, incentive pay is lower in
 the mission-oriented sector than in the profit-oriented sector
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Besley & Ghatak 2005: Competing for Workers: Unemployment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\shape smallcaps
proposition 4
\shape default
: 
\emph on
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{0}^{a}>n_{0}^{p}$
\end_inset

 (unemployment in the profit-oriented sector).
 Then the following matching 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is stable: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(a_{j}\right)=p_{j}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0,1,2$
\end_inset

 and the associated optimal contracts have the following features:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument item:1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph on
(a)
\end_layout

\end_inset

The fixed wage is set at the subsistence level 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{ij}^{*}=\underline{w}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0,1,2$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument item:1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph on
(b)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph on
The bonus payment in the mission-oriented sector is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b_{11}^{*}=b_{22}^{*}=\frac{\max\left\{ \bar{\theta},\hat{\pi}\right\} -\bar{\theta}}{2}
\]

\end_inset

and the bonus payment in the profit-oriented sector is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b_{00}^{*}=\frac{\pi_{0}}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument item:1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph on
(c)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph on
The optimal effort level solves: 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{ij}^{*}=b_{ij}^{*}+\bar{\theta}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{00}^{*}=b_{00}^{*}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

