Incentives Work: Getting Teachers to Come to School
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Duflo et al.
 2012: Introduction
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Access to primary school has increased dramatically in low-income countries,
 but school quality hasn't
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
65% of children in grades 2-5 in Indian government schools in 2006 couldn't
 read a simple paragraph (Pratham 2006)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
24% of teachers in India are absent in unannounced visits (Kremer et al
 2005)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This paper: Experiment and structural model of direct monitoring of para-teacher
s' attendance in India.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Ambiguous effect on presence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Standard labor supply model predicts more effort, but only if strong enough
 incentives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Incentives could crowd out intrinsic motivation (Benabou & Tirole 2006).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Teachers may stop working after reaching target income (Fehr & Goette 2007)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Duflo et al.
 2012: Introduction
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Will presence increase learning?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Multitasking means incentives for presence could crowd out other dimensions
 of effort (Holmstrom & Milgrom 1991).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Incentives may demotalize teacher or reduce their intrinsic motivation to
 teach.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
But if the main reason people fon't show up is the opportunity cost of being
 at the school and the marginal cost of teaching once you're at the school
 is low, this might just work.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Duflo et al.
 2012: Setting & Experiment
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The setting are rural nonformal education centers (NFEs) in Udaipur, Rajasthan,
 India.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In september 2003 Seva Mandir, the operator chose 120 schools for the experiment.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
In 60 schools the teachers got a camera and were told that one of the students
 had to take a photograph of the teacher with the children at the start
 and the end of the day.
 Cameras had a tamper-proof date & time function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The other 60 schools are controls
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Teachers' base salary was Rs.
 1,000 for at least 20 days of work per month.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Treatment teachers got a Rs.
 50 bonus for every day in excess of 20 days and a Rs.
 50 fine for each day of the 20 that they skip.
 Fines capped at Rs.
 500
\end_layout

\end_deeper
