\begin_layout Plain Layout
Duflo et al.
 2012: Dynamic Labor Supply Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Teachers on day 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\left\{ 1,\ldots,T_{m}\right\} $
\end_inset

 of month 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 value consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{tm}$
\end_inset

 and leisure 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{tm}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{tm}=U\left(C_{tm},L_{tm}\right)=\beta C_{tm}\left(\pi_{m}\right)+\left(\mu_{tm}-P\right)L_{tm}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is nonpecuniary cost of missing work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consumption depends on earned income 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{m}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 turns rupees of consumption into utility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $L_{tm}$
\end_inset

 is 1 if the teacher doesn't attend work, and zero otherwise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Leisure coefficient has deterministic and stochastic parts
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{tm}=\mu+\epsilon_{tm}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{tm}$
\end_inset

 is assumed to be normal.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Duflo et al.
 2012: Dynamic Labor Supply Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Not attending school has two costs: 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and a probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{m}\left(t,d\right)$
\end_inset

 of being fired that depends on the number of days worked 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 by time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in month 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 If they are fired, teachers get 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, their outside option.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Income in the treatment group is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{m}=500+50\max\left\{ 0,d_{m-1}-10\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

while in the control group 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{m}$
\end_inset

 is Rs.
 1000.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Control group has simple binary choice.
 Bellman equation on every day except last day of the month:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
V_{m}\left(t,d;\epsilon_{tm}\right) & =p_{m}\left(t,d\right)F+\left[1-p_{m}\left(t,d\right)\right]\times\\
 & \quad\max\left\{ \mu-P+\epsilon_{tm}+EV_{m}\left(t+1,d;\epsilon_{t,m+1}\right)\right.\\
 & \qquad\quad\left.,EV_{m}\left(t+1,d+1;\epsilon_{t,m+1}\right)\right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Duflo et al.
 2012: Dynamic Labor Supply Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Treatment group have a very different problem to solve since they face incentive
s for attendance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In periods 
\begin_inset Formula $t<T_{m}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
V_{m}\left(t,d;\epsilon_{tm}\right) & =p_{m}\left(t,d\right)+\left(1-p_{m}\left(t,d\right)\right)\times\\
 & \quad\max\left\{ \mu-P+\epsilon_{tm}+EV_{m}\left(t+1,d;\epsilon_{t,m+1}\right)\right.\\
 & \qquad\quad\left.,EV_{m}\left(t+1,d+1;\epsilon_{t,m+1}\right)\right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In period 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
V_{m}\left(T_{m},d;\epsilon_{T_{m},m}\right) & =p_{m}\left(T_{m},d\right)F+\left[1-p_{m}\left(T_{m},d\right)\right]\times\\
 & \quad\max\left\{ \mu-\bar{P}+\epsilon_{T_{m},m}+\beta\pi\left(d\right)\right.\\
 & \qquad\qquad+EV_{m+1}\left(1,0;\epsilon_{t,m+1}\right)\\
 & \qquad\quad\left.,\beta\pi\left(d+1\right)+EV_{m+1}\left(1,0;\epsilon_{t,m+1}\right)\right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Duflo et al.
 2012: Estimation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
In period 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $EV_{m+1}$
\end_inset

 doesn't depend on action in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}$
\end_inset

 so we can solve the model backwards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Need to make some assumptions about 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the data noone ever gets fired, so assume that teachers perceive 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{m}\left(t,d\right)=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Model 1: iid errors.
 Simplest case.
 In period 
\begin_inset Formula $t<T$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbb{P}\left(work;t,d,\theta\right) & =\mathbb{P}\left(\mu+\epsilon_{tm}+EV\left(t+1,d\right)<EV\left(t+1,d+1\right)\right)\\
 & =\mathbb{P}\left(\epsilon_{tm}<EV\left(t+1,d+1\right)-EV\left(t+1,d\right)-\mu\right)\\
 & =\Phi\left(EV\left(t+1,d+1\right)-EV\left(t+1,d\right)-\mu\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Duflo et al.
 2012: Estimation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Each value function can be computed using backword recursion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{imt}$
\end_inset

 be an indicator for working on day 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in month 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 Then the log likelihood is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
LLH\left(\theta\right) & =\sum_{i=1}^{N}\sum_{m=1}^{M_{i}}\sum_{t=1}^{T_{m}}\left[w_{imt}\mathbb{P}\left(work;t,d,\theta\right)\right.\\
 & \qquad\qquad\left.+\left(1-w_{imt}\right)\left(1-\mathbb{P}\left(work,t,d,\theta\right)\right)\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This likelihood is concave and can be evaluated quickly, no numerical integratio
n is needed.
 Just need to evaluate it at many points.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Duflo et al.
 2012: Estimation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Now introduce some serial correlation in two ways.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Approach 1: Serially correlated preference shocks
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{mt}=\mu+w_{m,t-1}\gamma
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Now the likelihood is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
LLH\left(\theta\right) & =\sum_{i=1}^{N}\sum_{m=1}^{M_{i}}\sum_{t=1}^{T_{m}}\left[w_{imt}\mathbb{P}\left(work;t,d,\theta,w_{m,t-1}\right)\right.\\
 & \qquad\qquad\left.+\left(1-w_{imt}\right)\left(1-\mathbb{P}\left(work,t,d,\theta,w_{m,t-1}\right)\right)\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Approach 2: Serially correlated cost shocks:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon_{mt}=\rho\epsilon_{m,t-1}+\nu_{mt}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Can't estimate this by ML, need to use Method of Simulated Moments.
 Match sequences of attendance of length 5.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


