The Value of Regulatory Discretion: Estimates from Environmental Inspections
 in India
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Duflo et al 2017: Introduction
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Pollution is high despite strict standards for emissions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Why aren't the standards enforced?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Typical explanations: Lack of resources, corruption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Gujarat Pollution Control Board (GPCB) has limited resources, so uses discretion
 to pick which plants to inspect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How does the regulator choose who to inspect? Would removing that discretion
 help or hurt enforcement?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Experiment and structural model in Gujarat to investigate these issues
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Duflo et al 2017: Context
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Industrial plants are subject to stringent air and water emissions standards
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
GPCB inspects plants to observe its condition, environmental management,
 and often collects pollution samples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Regulation mandates routine inspection.
 Every 90 days for large- or medium-scale plants, and once a year for small-scal
e plants.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
At baseline, 42% of control plants inspected less than prescribed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Penalties can be harsh.
 Regulator can mandate installation of abatement equipment, require a bond
 be posted against future performance, order utilities disconnected.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
